        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 300. <placeName type="townland">Island</placeName></name>,
                Co. <placeName type="county">Waterford</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                        target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WA032-029002"
                        >WA032-029002</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Possible Ecclesiastical</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>Situated just below the summit of a gentle NE-facing slope, with sea cliffs c. 130m to the S. This is possibly an early ecclesiastical site (WA032-029001-). 
                        The enclosure is a large, grass-covered circular area (diam. 85.5m E-W; 83.5m N-S) defined by an overgrown earthen field bank with internal 
                        and external stone-facing (Wth c. 2-3m; H c. 1-2m). The entrance (Wth 2.1m) at W is possibly modern. There is an ogham stone lying just inside the perimeter close to the entrance
                        with a small cross-inscribed stone (WA032-029004-) lying beside it (<ref
                            target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/historicenvironment/?SMRS=WA032-029001-"
                            >ASI database, 
                            www.archaeology.ie</ref>; see image below right). <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>Brash</author> 
                                (<date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >253</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> and <ref type="bibliog" target="#WES1906"><bibl><author>Westropp</author> 
                                        (<date when="1906">1906</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                            >250</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> both mention a local tradition that there was a killeen (unbaptised children's burial ground) at the site.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="material"/>Slate, in two fragments,<rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.42</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.49</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.15</measure>m
                        </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p><q>Inscription on two angles and the top (up-top-down), and, except for some
                            chipping, in good condition</q>
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                            <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >290</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. As
                        McManus indicates in his reading, there is space for an expected A between
                        the two Ns of CUN[A]NETAS. Also, it makes more sense to read MM than G for
                        the two strokes before UC[OI] <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1945"
                                >(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                            <date when="1945">1991</date>
                            <biblScope type="pp">7, 94</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <persName><w lemma="CUNANETAS">CUN<supplied reason="lost"
                            >A</supplied>NETAS</w></persName>
                    <w lemma="MAQI" type="formula">MAQ/I</w>
                    <w lemma="MUCOI" type="formula">MMUC/<supplied reason="lost">OI</supplied></w>
                    <persName><w lemma="NETA-SEGAMONAS">NETA-SEGAMONAS</w></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <ab>
                    <q>of Conda son of the descendant of Nad-Segamon</q>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list>
                    <item n="1"><p>This is one of the inscriptions listed by <ref type="bibliog"
                        target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1945"
                            >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >93-4</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> to be among the earliest in the
                        corpus showing no trace of vowel affection. It may be dated to the first
                        half, or the early second half, of the fifth century <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >97</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p> The personal name CUN[A]NETAS (OIr. <hi rend="italic">Conda</hi> for <hi rend="italic">Conne</hi>) contains
                            the commonly occuring element CUNA- and may be translated 'champion of
                            wolves' <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1945">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1945">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">102,
                                    106</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>

                    <item n="3"><p>The kindred or sept name NETA-SEGAMONAS 
                        consists of the element <hi rend="italic">Nad</hi>- 'sister's son, champion' and a personal
                        name <persName><hi rend="italic">Segamon</hi></persName>
                            <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1945">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1945">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">109-10,
                                    112</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. One theory is that this may be the
                        Gaulish name <persName><hi rend="italic">Segomo</hi></persName>
                            <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1945">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1945">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">179 n.
                                    46</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. It is noteworthy that a <hi rend="italic">Nia-Segamon</hi> is listed in the historical 
                        sources as a prehistoric king of Cashel <ref type="bibliog" target="#BHR2014">(<bibl><author>Bhreathnach</author>
                                <date when="2014">2014</date>, <biblScope type="pp">43-4</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. The fact that MUCOI NETA-SEGAMONAS 
                        '(of) the descendant of Nad/Nia-Segamon' is also found on an ogham stone at nearby
                        Ardmore I (<ref target="search.php?ciic=263">CIIC. 263</ref>) and possibly also Knockboy (<ref target="search.php?ciic=292">CIIC. 292</ref>) may suggest that this was a dynasty which
                        controlled the area of west Waterford in the 5th century.</p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Originally recorded by <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>Brash</author> 
                            (<date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >253-4</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> as 'lying in the middle of a field'
                            (enclosure). It was later incorporated with the surrounding wall and
                                'practically inaccessible'
                            <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >290</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> in the townland of <placeName type="townland">(Old)
                                Island</placeName> and barony of <placeName type="barony">Decies
                                    without Drum</placeName>. (GPS coordinates <geo>-7.481665, 52.113809</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location possibly original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">Lying on the ground close to the edge of the field
                            (enclosure) and near the modern entrance. The present location of this
                            stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WA032-029002"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>.</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>First published mention appears to be <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>Brash</author> 
                    (<date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                        >253-4</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. According to <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1907"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                    (<date when="1907">1907</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                        >196</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, a boy at the site told him that the stone once stood in the centre of the enclosure with the small cross-inscribed stone placed on top of it. Apart from sketches by <ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>Brash</author> 
                            (<date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >PL. XXXV.</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> and <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1907"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                    (<date when="1907">1907</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >197</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>,
                    no other representation or image of the stone appears to have been made. Attempts were made to record the stone in 3d in 2012 but due to wet weather and the awkward position of the stone the result was unsatisfactory. 
                    The 3d model is nonetheless made available here as a record of the stone. The site was re-visited in 2017 but was too overgrown to locate the stone. </p>
            </div>
